# Why I Started Taking Better Notes While Learning Cybersecurity

Link:https://medium.com/@rushivenkatadri/why-i-started-taking-better-notes-while-learning-cybersecurity-34cbe4a9339b


When I first started learning cybersecurity, I thought taking notes was a waste of time.

I believed I would remember everything after finishing a lab or watching a course.

A few weeks later, I realized I couldn't.

I would forget commands, testing steps, and even why a vulnerability existed.

That's when I started writing everything down.

---

## My Notes Are Not Perfect

I don't try to make my notes look beautiful.

They're simple.

Sometimes it's just:

- A Burp Suite request
- A Linux command
- A screenshot
- A mistake I made
- A lesson I don't want to forget

The goal isn't to impress anyone.

The goal is to make future me learn faster.

---

## Writing Helps Me Understand

I've noticed something interesting.

When I explain a topic in my own words, I understand it much better.

If I can't explain it simply, I probably haven't understood it well enough.

That's why I started documenting my journey through:

- GitHub repositories
- Medium articles
- LinkedIn posts

Not because I'm an expert.

Because writing helps me become better.

---

## Looking Back Feels Different

Sometimes I open notes I wrote a month ago.

Things that once looked confusing now seem simple.

That reminds me I've actually made progress.

It's easy to feel like you're not improving.

Looking back at old notes proves otherwise.

---

## What I'll Keep Doing

I'm still a beginner.

There are many topics I haven't explored yet.

But one habit I won't stop is documenting what I learn.

Even if no one reads my notes, they're already helping the person who needs them most—me.

---

## Final Thoughts

Cybersecurity isn't only about finding vulnerabilities.

It's also about building good habits.

For me, taking notes has become one of those habits.

And I think it's one of the best decisions I've made since starting this journey.

Thanks for reading.

